<br>
For the sake of argument lets say they dont violate the resolution requirements. If blix had come out and made a big deal out of this discovery before he verified it and the US used this as a pretext to declare war on Iraq only to find out later that it didnt violate the restrictions. Where then would blix's responsibility lie?<br>
<br>
I am not trying to excuse Sadam here. I do however think questioning Blix's profesionalism over this is unfair to a man that as far as I can tell is making every effort to acomplish a very difficult task as profesionaly as he can.<br>
<br>
The US is clearly looking for any reason to start this war. Blix carries a verry heavy wieght on his shoulders.The whole world is basicly hanging on what he says to make their decision on what to do. If you were in his position would you be so quick to start a war on unverified information?<br>
<br>
Do you really believe he had any illusions that people wouldnt pour over his report with a fine tooth comb? That he thought for a second that this information would be overlooked?<br>
<br>
Give the guy a break. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=telkandoretelenesis>Telkandore Telenesis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>You lookin' at me?</span><br>  Posts: 1015<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/9/03 7:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=473.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I understand your concern</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Powell talked about it in his report to the UN. Also the missles were declared they werent discovered.<br>
<br>
I know the drumbeat for war is hot and heavy but please try to sift through the BS propaganda.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
uhh yeah, all the more reason to confirm Powell's intelligence report that had been denied by Iraq and butchered by various commentators. And the missiles were declared but their distance was covered up and then... discovered. There's little difference here. And what BS propaganda? The first AP report I read on this said simply, &quot;Also in the 173 page report, Blix expresses his concern over an undeclared unmanned Iraqi drone discovered by inspectors on March 4.&quot; There was no mention of &quot;outrage&quot; from US officals, but the flag went up in my head immediately as I knew this was an odd thing for Blix to ignore in his oral report.  Just as I was about to post this thread I found the Times article while searching for a link to the AP article, which said that US officials were baffled as well. The &quot;propaganda&quot; did not affect me.<br>
<br>
Yes, Blix's job is not to make the case for war. It is to verify if Iraq is complying and to state in his oral presentations the areas in which Iraq is complying, possibly complying, not complying and possibly not complying. It <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>is</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> clear that this drone violates resolution 1441 in at least one area... it was not declared. He neglected to make mention of one very major instance in which Iraq did not comply by not declaring an unmanned drone which is said to have been test flighted at a distance of up to 500km.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If blix had come out and made a big deal out of this discovery before he verified it and the US used this as a pretext to declare war on Iraq only to find out later that it didnt violate the restrictions.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
When Blix first mentioned the Al Samoud missiles it was not clear whether they were capable of exceeding the UN's limits. He verified nothing then, he reported his suspicions even though not one test or calculation had been completed. Blix was suspicous of the missiles, he said as much in his oral report and said testing would soon be done to determine the missiles' capability. He is suspicous of this unmanned drone. He did not say as much in his oral report. Unmanned drones fall under the exact same limitations as missiles. Why make mention of possible missile violations which were not confirmed to have been able to exceed UN limits in an oral report but choose to bury an undeclared unmanned drone that's just as suspicious and no less dangerous than the Al Samoud's distance in a large document?<br>
<br>
He doesn't have to make a &quot;big deal&quot; out of it. He needs to report his findings in his oral report. It's simple. It would have taken 45 seconds to state this undeclared drone had been found, review the intelligence UNMOVIC has receieved about Iraqi unmanned test flights exceeding the 150km limit and state that testing will need to be done on this undeclared aircraft.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If you were in his position would you be so quick to start a war on unverified information?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Do you really believe he had any illusions that people wouldnt pour over his report with a fine tooth comb? That he thought for a second that this information would be overlooked?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Given that a &quot;big deal&quot; does not need to be made about this find in the oral presentation, you contradict yourself with these 2 quotes. Ask yourself this: Why did Colin Powell not know of the find until the report was handed out hours later when he made it clear that he was going to read from this report at the security council meeting, why did Blix go a completely different route with Al Samoud missiles, why did Blix not want to state in his oral presentation that inspectors had found <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>anything</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that was undeclared by Iraq when he has done so mulitple times in his past oral presentations?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Give the guy a break.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No one deserves a break in matters as serious as these, Esmann. Not Hussein, not Bush, not Blix. Blix has now demonstrated clear negligence on his part. I'm not going to give the guy a break when he is the most important figure in determining whether Iraq will be disarmed through peaceful or foreceful actions. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=telkandoretelenesis>Telkandore Telenesis</A> at: 3/9/03 8:58:18 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=esmann>Esmann</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/9/03 8:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=473.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Well you sound a lot more reasonable</span><hr size=1> I would just like to address one thing. Why did Blix speak about the missiles in his report.<br>
