Those 27 issues were in the hands of every UN member present during the meeting. Those 27 issues did not involve any major new discovery of a huge lethal undeclared aircraft. Those 27 issues involved requests, contradictions and requests unfulfilled, not discoveries. It's not comparable, the drone find was among a 6 page addendum which covered other areas not related to the main intention of the document, rather it was an odd stuffing of various discoveries and suspicions into a large document mainly directed at outstanding issues and cooperation.<br>
<br>
Read Blix's transcript. Colin Powell and Jack Straw also went over these issues after Blix briefly outlined them. No outrage is justified in that respect. Also in that addendum is stated suspicion that Iraq may still possess undeclared anthrax and more missiles that violate UN limits, but that was not hidden during Blix's oral report. The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>only</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> thing that didn't have at least half a sentence devoted to it that was mentioned in the 173 page document were the discovery of an undeclared Iraqi drone. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>“It’s incredible,” a senior diplomat of Angola said regarding the discovery of the undeclared drone. “This report is going to have a clearly defined impact on the people who are wavering. It’s a biggie.”</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Ya know about Angola? Their vote for the 2nd(err 18th) resolution was unlikely to be in favor of the US, Britain and Spain. To them, this is a big deal. What's a big deal to members of the security council deserves to be given at least a few <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>seconds</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of time during an oral presentation. You don't see anything extraordianary about this omission, but even countries that are weary of the US do, and the uproar over it by senior administration officials from US and Britain has not even started yet.<br>
<br>
His job on March 7 was not to disarm Iraq. His job on March 7 was to report the progress and issues related to the disarmement process. Because he wants inspections to continue for months more he pushed his own agenda by making light of a serious issue. He's a sly lawyer and knows how to work the people. The burying of a major discovery to understate the severity has worked at least on you.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;Inspectors are also engaged in examining Iraq's programs for remotely piloted vehicles. A number of sites have been inspected, with data being collected to assess the range and other capabilities of the various models found, and inspections are continuing in this area.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
